<HEADLINE>
Over 1,500 fowls culled in southern Bangladesh after detection of
bird flu
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, Jan. 27 (Xinhua)
</P>
<P>
Around 1,500 poultry birds were culled on Saturday in
Bangladesh's southern Bhola district, about 130 km southeast of
capital Dhaka, following detection of avian influenza, leading
newspaper The Daily Star reported Sunday.
</P>
<P>
District livestock officials collected samples of some dead
chickens from the area and sent those to Dhaka for laboratory
test after large number of fowls of three farms died during the
last few days.
</P>
<P>
As the avian influenza was detected, the district administration
in presence of deputy commissioner Belayet Hossain and joint
forces dumped the chickens under the ground.
</P>
<P>
The district administration also advised residents of 1 km square
mile to refrain from eating chickens affected by bird flu.
</P>
<P>
The avian influenza virus was first detected in a poultry farm in
Savar, about 30 km northwest of Dhaka, early in 2007.
</P>
<P>
Detections of avian influenza have been reported in several
districts across the country in the last one month. At least 50,
000 fowls were killed and thousands of eggs were destroyed in the
districts.
</P>
